Beyond Azure S-Q-L and Cosmos D-B, Azure offers several specialised managed database services. This topic covers Azure Cache for Redis — the most commonly used caching layer in Azure architectures — and then surveys the managed open-source relational database services: Azure Database for PostgreSQL, MySQL, and MariaDB.

Let us start with Azure Cache for Redis.

Azure Cache for Redis is a fully managed, in-memory data store based on the open-source Redis project. It provides sub-millisecond data access for caching, session storage, real-time leaderboards, pub/sub messaging, and distributed locking. By keeping frequently accessed data in memory, Redis dramatically reduces the load on backend databases and removes a common bottleneck in high-traffic applications.

Azure Cache for Redis comes in five tiers. The Basic tier is for development and testing — it has no S-L-A and no replication. The Standard tier is the production entry point: it runs a primary and a replica instance and provides a 99.9% S-L-A. The Premium tier adds clustering with up to 10 shards, V-Net injection for private network access, data persistence to Blob Storage, and passive geo-replication. The Enterprise tier uses the full Redis Enterprise engine, supports much larger memory up to 14 terabytes, enables active geo-replication across regions, and includes Redis modules such as Search, J-S-O-N, and TimeSeries. The Enterprise Flash tier uses a combination of N-V-Me S-S-D and R-A-M to extend capacity cost-effectively for very large datasets.

Redis supports eight data types that make it useful for a wide range of patterns. Strings are binary-safe byte sequences used for simple key-value caching and counters. Hashes store a set of field-value pairs under a single key — ideal for representing objects like user profiles. Lists are ordered linked lists supporting push and pop from either end — used for message queues and recent activity feeds. Sets are unordered collections of unique members — used for tags and tracking unique visitors. Sorted Sets, also called Z-Sets, associate a floating-point score with each member and keep members ordered by score — the natural data structure for leaderboards and rate limiting. Bitmaps allow you to set and test individual bits on a string key — useful for feature flags and tracking user online status at very low memory cost. HyperLogLog provides a probabilistic approximation of the number of unique elements — used for approximate unique counts with near-constant memory usage. And Streams are an append-only log with consumer groups, similar in concept to Apache Kafka — used for event sourcing and I-o-T telemetry.

There are three common caching patterns. The Cache-Aside pattern, also called Lazy Loading, is the most widely used. The application checks the cache first. On a cache miss, it reads from the database, writes the result to the cache with a T-T-L, and returns the data. Subsequent reads hit the cache until the T-T-L expires. Only data that is actually requested gets cached, so the cache stays lean. The Write-Through pattern means every write goes to the cache first, and the cache synchronously writes through to the database. Reads always hit the cache and data is never stale, but every write has double latency — once to the cache, once to the database. The Write-Behind or Write-Back pattern writes to the cache and the cache asynchronously flushes to the database later. This allows very high write throughput but carries a risk of data loss if the cache fails before flushing.

T-T-L, or Time To Live, sets an expiry on individual keys so stale data is automatically removed. When the cache is full, Redis applies an eviction policy to free memory. The most common policy for a cache is allkeys-lru, which evicts the least recently used keys across all keys. The volatile-lru policy only evicts keys that already have a T-T-L set, leaving keys without a T-T-L untouched. The allkeys-lfu policy evicts the least frequently used keys. And noeviction is the default — it returns an error when memory is full without removing any data, which is appropriate when Redis is used as a primary data store rather than a cache.

Now let us look at Redis advanced features.

Redis is an in-memory store — by default, data is lost if the instance restarts. The Premium tier adds two persistence options. R-D-B, or Redis Database Backup, takes periodic point-in-time snapshots and saves them to Azure Blob Storage. On restart, data is restored from the last snapshot — acceptable for use cases where some data loss is tolerable. A-O-F, or Append-Only File, logs every write command to disk before acknowledging it to the client, providing near-zero data loss at the cost of higher write overhead. Use R-D-B for periodic backups and A-O-F when data durability is critical.

Clustering splits data across multiple shards using 16,384 hash slots. Redis consistently hashes each key to a slot, and each shard owns a range of slots. The Premium tier supports up to 10 shards. Each shard has its own primary and replica. Clustering multiplies total memory capacity and commands-per-second throughput proportionally. Client libraries handle slot routing automatically.

For geo-replication, the Premium tier provides passive geo-replication: one writable primary and one or more read-only secondaries in other regions. Failover requires manual promotion. The Enterprise tier provides active geo-replication: all replicas are writable and conflicts are resolved using Last-Writer-Wins. This enables a true active-active multi-region Redis topology.

For network security, Premium tier caches support V-Net injection — the cache is deployed inside your V-Net subnet with a private I-P and no public endpoint. Standard and Basic tier caches can use Private Link to assign a private endpoint. Always disable public network access and use private connectivity in production.

Redis is the standard solution for distributed session storage in web applications. Instead of each web server storing session data in local memory — which breaks when you add a second server — all servers read and write session data from a shared Redis instance. This enables stateless horizontal scaling without sticky sessions.

Redis pub/sub lets producers publish messages to named channels and consumers subscribe. It is a fire-and-forget mechanism with no message persistence — if a subscriber is offline, messages are lost. For more reliable messaging use Redis Streams, which provide an append-only log with consumer groups and message acknowledgement, similar to Kafka. For enterprise-grade messaging with ordering and dead-lettering, use Azure Service Bus.

Now let us look at the managed open-source relational database services.

Azure Database for PostgreSQL Flexible Server is the current recommended deployment option. It provides a fully managed community PostgreSQL engine — Azure handles patching, backups, and high availability. Zone-redundant H-A deploys a standby replica in a different availability zone with automatic failover in 60 to 120 seconds. Same-zone H-A keeps the standby in the same zone for lower cost when zone resilience is not required. Up to five cross-region read replicas provide read scale-out and can be used for disaster recovery. The stop/start feature lets you pause a server to stop compute billing — storage continues to be billed. Point-in-time restore is available within a 1 to 35 day retention window. The Burstable tier uses B-series V-Ms and is cost-effective for development and test workloads with intermittent C-P-U usage. Flexible Server includes built-in P-g-Bouncer for connection pooling, which is essential for high-concurrency applications that would otherwise exhaust PostgreSQL's connection limit. Popular extensions like PostGIS for geospatial queries, pgcrypto, pg_partman for table partitioning, and pg_stat_statements for query performance monitoring are all supported.

Azure Database for MySQL Flexible Server follows the same architecture. It supports MySQL 5.7 and 8.0, zone-redundant H-A with automatic failover, up to 10 cross-region read replicas, stop/start for compute cost savings, and point-in-time restore within 1 to 35 days. It is the right choice for L-A-M-P stack applications and any workload built on MySQL.

Azure Database for MariaDB is a managed community MariaDB service. However, it is being retired on September 19, 2025. Microsoft recommends migrating all MariaDB workloads to Azure Database for MySQL Flexible Server, which is compatible with MariaDB for most application use cases.

All three open-source database services share a common security baseline: Entra I-D authentication, private endpoint or V-Net integration, Transparent Data Encryption at rest, enforced S-S-L connections, automated backups with point-in-time restore, read replicas, and Microsoft Defender for advanced threat detection.

To summarise. Use Azure Cache for Redis to add sub-millisecond caching in front of any database — the Cache-Aside pattern is the most practical starting point. Use the Standard tier for production, the Premium tier when you need clustering, persistence, or V-Net injection. Set T-T-L on all cached data and choose an appropriate eviction policy — allkeys-lru for a pure cache. Use Sorted Sets for leaderboards and rate limiting. Use pipelines to batch Redis commands and reduce round trips. For relational open-source workloads, use PostgreSQL Flexible Server as the default — it has the richest feature set, zone-redundant H-A, and built-in connection pooling. Use MySQL Flexible Server for existing MySQL workloads. Migrate away from MariaDB before the September 2025 retirement date. And always use private endpoints or V-Net integration for production databases and caches.

In the next topic, we will look at Azure Service Bus, Event Grid, and Event Hubs — the messaging and event streaming services that connect loosely coupled application components.
